'''Garabed T. K. Giragossian''' was an [[Armenians|Armenian]] living in [[Boston]] who is remembered for developing a [[perpetual motion]] device shortly after the turn of the 20th century.  He [[immigrated]] to [[United States|America]] in 1891. In 1917, Giragossian claimed, reportedly [[fraud]]ulently, to have developed a "free energy machine". The assignment of the patent to the United States government was conditionally accepted in Pub. Res. 65-21, {{USStat|40|435}}, enacted on February 8, 1918, and authorized the [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] to form a scientific committee to investigate the machine. The committee issued a report on July 1, 1918 finding that the principles were not sound.<ref>{{citation | title= Automotive Industries | volume= 39 | publisher= Chilton company | page= 34 | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dM8qAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA34 }}</ref> According to an editorial in the Scientific American in 1918, Giragossian claimed that the machine, named Garabed, took energy out of the cosmos and turned it into mechanical motion.<ref name=JAMA>Discoveries and Discoverers. JAMA Revisited, August 7, 2018 JAMA. 2018;320(5):512. doi:10.1001/jama.2017.12501, Originally published JAMA. August 10, 1918;71(6):465</ref>

Editors of the [[Journal of the American Medical Association]] compared him and his methods with [[Quackery|quack]]s in the medical world; they pointed out that he could not answer the question what qualifications he had to undertake his work, and that he repeatedly only replied, he was an honest man and that he could prove it with signatures of friends and sponsors. They deplored the waste of time of "scientific men in investigating alleged discoveries by men who are utterly lacking in the fundamental qualifications needed [...]."<ref name=JAMA/>

Supposedly involved in a [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]], [[Woodrow Wilson]] signed a [[Resolution (policy debate)|resolution]] offering him protection.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}} The device was a giant [[flywheel]] that was charged up with [[energy]] slowly and put out a lot of energy for just a [[second]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}

