[[File:Hydrogenoxalate.svg|thumb|right| Wireframe model of hydrogenoxalate]]
'''Hydrogenoxalate''' or '''hydrogen oxalate''' is an [[anion]] with [[chemical formula]] {{chem|HC|2|O|4|-}} or {{chem|HO|2|C–CO|2|-}}, derived from [[oxalic acid]] by the loss of a single [[proton]]; or, alternatively, from the [[oxalate]] anion {{chem|C|2|O|4|2-}} by addition of a proton.

The name is also used for any [[salt (chemistry)|salt]] containing this anion, such as [[sodium hydrogenoxalate|NaHC<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>]], [[potassium hydrogenoxalate|KHC<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>]], or [[ammonium hydrogenoxalate|NH<sub>3</sub>HC<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>]].  Hydrogenoxalates may also be called (especially in older literature) '''bioxalates''', '''acid oxalates''', or '''monobasic oxalates'''.

