{{Italic title}} '''''Treatise on Radioactivity''''' ({{lang-fr|Traité de Radioactivité}}) is a two-volume book from the year 1910 written by the [[Polish people|Polish]] [[scientist]] [[Marie Curie]] as a survey on the subject of [[radioactivity]].<ref>{{cite book|author=John Daintith|title=Biographical Encyclopedia of Scientists, Third Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqTNfnKJVPAC&pg=PA163|date=18 August 2008|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4200-7272-3|page=163}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Catharine M. C. Haines|title=International Women in Science: A Biographical Dictionary to 1950|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HftdjMNDvwIC&pg=PA78|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-090-1|page=78}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Suzanne Le-May Sheffield|title=Women and Science: Social Impact and Interaction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G1wZeK15EM8C&pg=PR20|year=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-460-8|page=XX}}</ref> She was awarded her second [[Nobel Prize]] in the following year after the publication of the book.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lemelson.mit.edu/resources/marie-curie|title=Marie Curie {{!}} Lemelson-MIT Program|website=lemelson.mit.edu|access-date=2016-05-05}}</ref> The book, which was dedicated to her newly deceased collaborator and husband [[Pierre Curie]], has been described as "a classic synthesis of current research on radioactivity by scientists of the early 20th century."<ref>http://library.brown.edu/exhibit/exhibits/show/evolution-of-chemistry/modern-chemistry----/marie-curie</ref> It was published by the Paris publisher Gauthier-Villars.
